column505: The cave is also known as Shiva caves, the literal translation of the real name Gogarbha is Cow's womb. You can reach the cave from a road from Gokarna town or there is a pathway from Ramteertha temple (approx 2 km). It's historic and a well designed cave with ventilation for air and light. I was told by the person in the picture (Swami Shivanand),  the cave is from the era of Ravaana. He maintains the cave while he visits here between December to February. Do carry a torch (cellphone torch won't justify the light to watch the inner caves and animals in) if you wish to see the bats and red frogs in the cave. Red frogs can be spotted in the cracks of the first cave turn on the left side. There are a few other caves within which lead to some other place, but with time they are blocked. I had a good time talking to Swami Shiva.

It's easy to find and road leading to temple from the main road is well. Although the temple has entrance from 3 different direction,  out of which one which is holds the main tower is closed.
Temple hosts a unique sculpture of Shiva sitting on Nandi along with Parvathi, which is said to be bought from Sourastra, hence also called "Sourastra Somanatha". A mirror is kept behind the idol so that devotee can see the Parvathi sitting at the back of Shiva.
The temple is restored with the help of ASI and financial support of Infosys foundation. You will find number of small temples around main temple all belong to different eras, being from Badami Chalukya to Vijayanaga.
A large well is just behind the temple, with steps to access the bottom of the same.
You will also find lot of inscriptions in the campus.

Museum is maintained by ASI and the entry fee here is 5₹. There are some collectibles on display here whiich we’re found around the area near the caves.

Their are many temples around Badami which are more or less in ruined shape. Lots of figures seen at the museum are from those temples which were destroyed over time.

Good details have been put up there if you want to understand a little more about Badami and it’s caves and temples.

Right from here you can also hike up to the northern side of the Badami fort. There is no entrance fee for that.

A visit here would be good. Would take around 30 min to cover it. Their is a small parking lot in case you are taking your own vehicle.

You can also hire an auto to reach here.

column505:
No shades anywhere. Can get very hot and Sunny in the afternoon.

We came here to spend some time while on the way back from Udupi, unfortunately was too hot and sunny. But we did walk to the end of the sea walk, there are no shades anywhere along the path way. Even the parking lot is open and gets very hot.

There are many stalls selling ice creams and refreshments. There is also a public restroom at the parking lot. Tickets to the St Mary’s Island need to be booked at the kiosk at the end of the parking lot. Expect long queues especially during holiday season.

The water channels are clean and the area generally well maintained. You can watch the fishing boats come and go from the harbour.

You also have to pay for entry to the port (40 Rs for SUV) and the parking lot (30 Rs)
On the whole a good place to walk around. Would prefer the evening time.

column662:
The Chalukya Shiva Temple (earlier known as Lad Khan Temple), dedicated to Shiva, is one of the oldest Hindu temples and is located in the group of monuments at Aihole in the state of Karnataka, India. Formerly dated to the 7th or 8th century, it is now dated to about the 5th century. It is located to the south of the Durga temple, Aihole.

The temple shows clear signs of following early timber models, none of which have survived. This is seen for example in the construction of the roof of the mandapa. The temple consists of a shrine (garba griha) with a mandapa in front of it, and a covered path for circumambulating the sanctuary, seen in other very early temples. The mukha mandapa is situated in front of the sanctum and consists of a set of 12 carved pillars. The sabha mandapa leads to the maha mandapa and the pillars are arranged to form two concentric squares. The walls have floral patterns on them and the windows have lattice work done in the northern style. Facing the sanctum, a second smaller sanctum is situated above the center of the hall whose outer walls have many carved images.

Originally dedicated to Vishnu, now the main shrine houses a Shiva Linga with a Nandi. The temple was built in a Panchayatana style, indicating a very early experiment in temple construction. The special feature of this temple is that it starts with a rectangular structure and ends with a square structure. Based on a wooden construction design, the square and rectangular plan has a steep roof, which is an adaptation of wooden styles in stone.

The maha mandapa is open to exterior by large windows between the pillars. The roof above the maha mandapa shows a turret as a first version of the future forms of tower: shikharas in north India and vimanas in the south

column505:
Located on the Camp Road in Belgaum in Karnataka, Military Mahadev Temple is one of the prime attractions in the city that has been built and maintained by the Indian Army. Founded in 1955 by Lieutenant General S.M. Shrinagesh, General Officer, and Commander-in-Chief Southern Command, the temple is situated in the heart of a lush green park. In addition to that, there is also a play area for the kids.

The foundation stone of Military Mahadev Temple was laid on January 18, 1954. The temple was opened to public on January 24, 1955 by Lieutenant General S.M. Shrinagesh, General Officer and Commander-in-Chief Southern Command.

Military Mahadev Temple has undergone several renovations and modifications through the years and the dome has been completely changed. There is a religious ritual practised every Monday called Samuhik Panchamrit, also called as the collective offering of the Panchamrit. This Panchamrit is made of four important elements - honey, yogurt, ghee, and sugar. The most important festival celebrated here is Mahashivratri. It has undergone renovations with a new dome built in the original style and carvings similar to those in other South Indian temples.

The temple remarkably clean and well-maintained. It is so called because of its long-standing use for worship by army personnel and of course, it was later thrown open to the public.

column505:
As per history, A guy who came to sell 'Sasive Kaalu' made a huge profit in this kingdom, so he made this beautiful Ganesha Idol in the memory of the king who ruled at that time.

This statue of Lord Ganesha is around 8 feet tall and is kept in an open pavilion. It is said that the stomach of the deity resembles the shape of a mustard seed and hence the name as ‘sasivekalu’ means mustard seed in Kannada. The lower left hand and the trunk of the statue are broken, and the stomach of the statue of the deity is tied with a snake. Legend has it that Lord Ganesha ate too much and hence tied a snake around His belly to prevent it from bursting! The statue is located in the southern part of Hemakuta Hill, not too far from Kadalekalu Ganesha Temple.

column662: The Sasivekalu Ganesha, named after Ganesha's mustard seed-shaped belly, is near the Krishna temple south-west of the Kadalekalu Ganesha. It is a 2.4 metres (7.9 ft)-high monolith that was also carved in-situ from extant rock. The Sasivekalu Ganesha is carved with his mother Parvati, in whose lap he sits. She is only visible from the back of the statue. The monument is housed inside an open-pillared mandapa; the left hand and tusk have been damaged.

column662:
I recently visited the 800-year-old Harihareshwara Temple in Harihar and I was blown away by the beauty and rich cultural history of this place. Situated on the banks of the Tungabadra River, this temple was built by the Hoysala Empire's General Polalva during the reign of King Vira Narasimha II and it truly showcases the remarkable architectural skills of the ancient Hindus.

As soon as I entered the temple grounds, I felt a sense of peace and positive energy. The monolithic architecture of the temple was truly awe-inspiring and I was amazed by the intricate carvings and details on the walls and pillars.

I highly recommend visiting this temple to anyone interested in Hindu culture and history. It's a truly unique and special place that will leave you feeling rejuvenated and inspired. Do make sure to take the time to explore the surroundings and appreciate the beauty of the Tungabadra River.

Overall, the Harihareshwara Temple is a must-visit for anyone if you come to Karnataka, a temple cannot be rated but I rating here the cleanliness and temple authorities and I give it a 5-star rating.

column662:
There's 11 Elephant's stables. All of them are interconnected with each other. There is entry fee of Rs.40 per Indian adult. Inside this complex there are plenty of historical monuments.

The whole building looks symmetric with respect to this central hall. The tower of the central hall resembles (though mostly destroyed) more like that of temples. However the five pairs of domes on either side are of Islamic in style. They are better preserved and of alternating patterns. Metal hooks (used to tie the elephants) on the inside roof can be seen. At the rear of each hall are small manhole type openings for the mahouts to enter the elephant compartments. It's one of the UNESCO World Heritage Site

A big Lawn Area to sit and relax, fresh air it was awesome experience.. Try to visit in the morning or evening.

column662:
Great initiative Sammilan Sir. Truly a great place to find the winged beauties.

The park provides the necessary freedom for the beautiful creatures. They can be found freely flattering around with their colourful wings. It is a natural habitat which provides conducive conditions so that the butterflies of various kinds are attracted to the park.

While strolling around the park we can distinctly see butterflies lay eggs, eggs there hatching into caterpillars, the caterpillars turn into pupa and also a beautiful butterfly emerge from a pupa.

The park is a home for some of the rare species like the Blue Nawab, Southern Birdwing which is the largest butterfly found in India and is endemic to south India. The Malabar Banded Peacock, considered as India’s 3rd beautiful butterfly and also an endemic to South India can be found here.

As a photography lover I really loved this place a lot. A great experience and a memorable one. Its worth the visit.

column662:
The giant statue of Lord Narasimha sitting in cross-legged Yoga position on the coil of a giant seven-headed Sesha, is one the best reminders of the virtues of Vijayanagara Empire and at the same time, the brutual destruction of the Hampi by the invaders who had no civility to understand the spirituality behind such great piece of art.

The original statue included the image of Goddess Lakshmi sitting on the lap of Lord Narasimha.

The invaders destroyed image of Goddess Lakshmi except the Goddess's hand which is still visible resting on the shoulder of Lord Narasimha.

A poignant reminder of fostering art and spirituality and at the same time callous looting and destruction of spirituality by the invaders.

Gem of Bhemghad ❤️

Vajra poha name it's self says it's a Diamond 💎 Falling like a beaten rice.

Very less known and hardly visited by anyone can only accessible only from the month of November to may.

Without forest department permission it's impossible to visit this place 🙌

Note: ( There is no guarantee that the person who goes will comes back safely)

So think twice and decide whether to visit or not.

This falls is located in the core region of Bhemghad tiger reserve.

That's the main reason why this place is restricted and not allowed for public.

As per my personal experience this place and the falls is not so easy as it looks in the pictures or videos.

One life,one precious life so don't take blind risk.

If u get permission from the department visit madi along with the forest officials or with the guard.

It's 6km Trek up and down  and it's takes three hours to reach the falls one side and three hours to return and u need to cross rivers twice to thrice.

Don't waste time near the waterfalls just return back before the dark.

I never recommend anyone to visit this place it's your own risk if anything happens no one is responsible.

Note: Be a responsible traveller/ Tourist whatever you bring just carry them back aste 🤟

The most neglected Historical Monument in Karnataka must be the #SadashivgadFort.

The #ArchaelogyDept, if it exists, has neglected this Fort and Sadashivgad Hill, since 5 decades ago, when it was split into two to make way for the #KaliBridge and the #NH66 aka #NH17 then and now the remainder is being levelled.

The major portion was leased by the #TourismDept and given away for running some resort  (God only knows who goes there) and no action was  taken when a Tunnel find was reported in #TimesofIndia dt.21Apr2012 and a #Canon find was again reported on 3Mar2016.

Taken over by the Maratha King Chatrapathi Shivaji in 1655, it was
ReConstructed by Sonde SadashivNayaka aka  SadashivLingaRaja  and his son BasavaLingaRaja in 1698, who named it after his father Raja of Sonda King Sadashiva Nayaka as Fort Sadashivagada.

The invaders Portuguese in 1752 and British General Mathews brought it down in 1783.

India s Archaeology Dept has so far ignored this Fort.

Hampi is a UNESCO World Heritage Site located in the Bellary district of Karnataka state.  The Hampi World Heritage covers an area of approximately 26 square km on either side of the Tungabhadra River.

The Area includes several monuments and structures that offer a glimpse into the grandeur of the Vijayanagara Empire who ruled from 1336 AD until its fall and destruction in 1565 AD.

Some of the popular sites in the Hampi are:
•	Virupaksha Temple complex
•	Vittala Temple complex
•	Hazara Rama Temple
•	Zanana Complex
•	Elephant stables and, Lotus Mahal
•	Royal Enclosure
•	Achyutaraya Temple
•	Edaru Bhaavana
•	Sasive Kalu Ganesha Temple
•	Mathanga Hill
•	Anjanadri Hill
•	Narasimha Temple, Badavi Linga
•	Krishna Temple
•	Uddana Virabhadra Temple
•	Prasanna Virupaksha Temple
•	Hampi Archeological Museum

A visit to Hampi is a must for anyone interested in the rich Indian cultural heritage and that grandeur of the Vijayanagara Empire.

The amount of time needed to have a full appreciation of Hampi depends on your interests and the pace of your visit since Hampi is a vast area and monuments and ruins are widely scattered across the World Heritage Area.

We spent six days in Hampi during mid January. If you are interested in exploring all of the major monuments in Hampi, it is recommended that you spend at least 3 days.

Don’t miss to see the sunrise from the top of Mathanga Hill and sunset from Anjanadri Temple.

Awesome!!!

column505:
An impressive and ornate structure that stupifies visitors more than 500 years after it was built. Located quite close to the Royal Enclosure, it is believed to have been got constructed by Achyuta Raya, the king as a private nathing chamber for himself and his queens.
The simple exterior and it's façade basically conceals the ornate architecture of its interior, which is different from any other public or private bath, of which there are several in Hampi.
The bath is about 6 feet deep, rectangular in shape, and is surrounded by pillared pavilions and a walkway. Steps lead down into the bath & the ceiling is open to the skies. The water is supplied through an aqueduct and the building is surrounded by a moat.

column505:
The fortress of the Bahmani Sultanate, Bidar Fort today (or what remains of it) is a must visit for history lovers and architecture enthusiasts. It's about 3 hours away from Hyderabad and a day trip from there is ideal.

The fort complex is quite large, however the areas one can visit aren't as expansive. The complex also houses a museum and a cafeteria. The cafeteria was closed during our visit, however. The complex also houses neat restrooms.

Car parking is available, although it isn't very large. Having said that, it's sufficient for the crowds it draws at the moment.

There is no entry fee currently. Visitors are allowed inside the premises during visiting hours. We heard from friends that the fort complex is shut on Fridays, so plan accordingly.

Bidar also houses the Bahmani tombs and the Ashtoor tombs. They are a 10 minute drive from Bidar Fort. One must definitely visit the tombs as well

Overall, the fort has been well restored and it looks like some more work is underway. It's a good place to visit, will be even better after the entire place is restored and done up.

column505:
If you like birds, or are a birder, you must visit this place. Jan to March is the best time if you want to see nesting behaviour of Spot-billed Pelicans, Spoonbills, Painted Storks, various heron and egret species, Little and Indians cormorants, Stone Curlews or Thick-knees, and River Terns. There are several other species as well, though they are a bit difficult to spot on the walking trails. There are 2-3 bird watching towers for photography and birding.

There is also a well created but small information centre that's interactive and engaging.

Boating is available for large groups and small - you can hire a special boat for your group at 2000rs. The boatmen help you identify the birds as well. Marsh crocodiles resting on rocks is a grand sight too.

There is a long walking/hiking trail, children's play areas, a food court+canteen serving simple fare, a sweet corn booth, and a sugarcane stall. Toilets are clean and there's a baby care room as well. Pets are not allowed.

Entry tickets cost Rs.75 per adult, plus camera fees up to Rs.600 if you are carrying a DSLR.

column662:
One of the most beautiful waterfalls in Karnataka.
This waterfall keeps up with the saying "Difficult roads often lead to beautiful destinations. " But here it would be BAD ROADS instead of DIFFICULT.
Roads are in very bad condition and it's very sad to see such beautiful destinations are still underdeveloped.
One needs to pay the entrance plus parking fees and then a short walk of 5min to see the water falls.
You can take a risk climbing/ sliding through the rocks to get a closer view of the falls which I would not recommend as the water flow might increase anytime depending upon the rainfall in the upper catchment area of the waterfalls. There are incidents where people get stuck on either side of the falls and forest guards spend hours together to bring them back safely.
Also the place has been neatly maintained and it's good to see such a beautiful destination very clean .
Get your own food / water / snacks / medicine or any stuff that you might need as the distance to the main town is around 25kms and it takes close to an hour or more to reach back considering the bad condition roads.
